items.name: Consent
items.label:
Hi,

Thank you for choosing to take part in this study.
In this study we aim to understand the experience of international medical students and the challenges that they face. We are particularly focussing on the effect of daily interactions on your well-being. This study consists of three main parts: (1) Study Entry [day 1 - right now], where we check your eligibility for the study and ask you for some general information about yourself, (2) the Experience Recaps [days 2 - 31], short daily questionnaires around lunch- and dinner time about your day and your interactions with other people, and (3) the Conclusion Survey [day 32], where we ask you to answer some broader questions and to briefly reflect on the study period. 

__The Study and the Payment__
1. Study Entry:
    + a. Informed Consent + Eligibility Survey: We will ask you some short questions to see whether you are eligble for the survey. 
    + b. Payment Details: We will ask you your paymeny details. For your privacy and anonymity, this is a seperate questionnaire and the data will be stored in a different system. 
    + c. Entry Survey: A start questionnaire (appr. 25 minutes) including general information, and your relations to the Dutch. (**2 Euros**)
2. Experience Recaps: 30 days of short reflection surveys (appr. 3-5 minutes) on your interactions twice a day. (**1 Euro per Recap; 2 Euro per day**)
3. Conclusion Survey: On the last day we will conclude with a final questionnaire (appr. 25 minutes) with some questions on your habits and a reflection of the study. (**2 Euros**)

**You can earn a <u>total of 64 Euros</u>. The payment will be determined based on your participation (i.e., how often you fill out the Experience Recaps) and will be transferred to your account once the study is concluded.**

__Your Privacy is Important__
Your participation is completely confidential and anonymous. No identifying information will be stored. Only members of the research team will have access to the survey data, but even they cannot link the data to any single person. Please feel free to answer all questions openly and honestly.

__Your Rights__
You can decide whether or not to participate in the study.
You can leave the study at any time.

__Risks__
There are no known risks associated with this study.
But please note that it is absolutely common and normal to not have social interactions every day.

__Questions__
We will be happy to answer questions about the study outcomes after your completion. Should you have technical questions or complaints feel free to contact us at:
j.kreienkamp@rug.nl / m.agostini@rug.nl.

units.condition:
formr::formr_connect('j.kreienkamp@rug.nl', '0815')
df <- formr::formr_raw_results('AOTM_Eligibility') 
df <- df[!is.na(df$ended),]
df$eligGroup <- factor(df$eligGroup, levels = c("eligible: BSc English", "eligible: MSc Jn Coschap", "eligible: MSc Sr Coschap", "eligible: MSc Other"))
dfUnique <- df[match(unique(df$e_mail), df$e_mail), ]

AOTM_Eligibility$elig == "not eligible" |
(AOTM_Eligibility$eligGroup == "eligible: BSc English" && table(dfUnique$eligGroup)["eligible: BSc English"]>80) | 
(AOTM_Eligibility$eligGroup == "eligible: MSc Jn Coschap" && table(dfUnique$eligGroup)["eligible: MSc Jn Coschap"]>51) | 
(AOTM_Eligibility$eligGroup == "eligible: MSc Sr Coschap" && table(dfUnique$eligGroup)["eligible: MSc Sr Coschap"]>51) | 
(AOTM_Eligibility$eligGroup == "eligible: MSc Other" && table(dfUnique$eligGroup)["eligible: MSc Other"]>51) | 
(AOTM_Eligibility$elig == "eligible" && table(df$e_mail)[AOTM_Eligibility$e_mail]>1)

items.name: OutroTxt
items.label:
Thank you. You made it through the entry questionnaire. During the upcoming 4 weeks we will send you super short daily questionnaires - the Experience Recaps. They only take a couple of minutes and focus on the interactions you had with Dutch or non-Dutch people since the last Experience Recap. There will be two per day. We will send you one for the morning (at around noon) and one for the afternoon (at around 7 pm). To keep the timeframe consistent, each of the short Recaps will be accessible for seven hours. Keep in mind that answering the Recaps is only possible within these seven hours. Please also take the Recap even if you had no interactions at all. Note, that it is absolutely normal and common to not have interactions. Whether or not you had an interaction, morning or evening, each Recap is worth 1 Euro and will automatically be added to your account. That is a coffee at IKEA, a song on iTunes, a pair of flip-flops at Zeeman, or a house in Italy for every Recap (for more great 1 Euro inspirations click here). Payment of the daily Recaps:
Sections Time(est.) Euro
Entry Questionnaire 0:25 hr 2 €
up to 60 Experience Recaps (4:00 min / Recap) 4:00 hr 60 €
Exit Questionnaire 0:20 hr 2 €
Total 4:45 hr 64 €
(=13.50€/hr)

Lastly, make sure to click "Submit this Survey" to finish this questionnaire and earn your first 2 Euro. See you tomorrow. The "International Medical Student Experience" study team
items.label_parsed:
Thank you. You made it through the entry questionnaire.

During the upcoming 4 weeks we will send you super short daily questionnaires - the Experience Recaps.
They only take a couple of minutes and focus on the interactions you had with Dutch or non-Dutch people since the last Experience Recap.
There will be two per day. We will send you one for the morning (at around noon) and one for the afternoon (at around 7 pm). To keep the timeframe consistent, each of the short Recaps will be accessible for seven hours. Keep in mind that answering the Recaps is only possible within these seven hours.

Please also take the Recap even if you had no interactions at all. Note, that it is absolutely normal and common to not have interactions.
Whether or not you had an interaction, morning or evening, each Recap is worth 1 Euro and will automatically be added to your account. That is a coffee at IKEA, a song on iTunes, a pair of flip-flops at Zeeman, or a house in Italy for every Recap (for more great 1 Euro inspirations click here).

Payment of the daily Recaps:

Sections Time(est.) Euro
Entry Questionnaire 0:25 hr 2 €
up to 60 Experience Recaps (4:00 min / Recap) 4:00 hr 60 €
Exit Questionnaire 0:20 hr 2 €
Total 4:45 hr 64 €
(=13.50€/hr)


Lastly, make sure to click "Submit this Survey" to finish this questionnaire and earn your first 2 Euro.

See you tomorrow.
The "International Medical Student Experience" study team

Exit Questionnaire 2 €

<script> 
     $(document).ready ( function() {
        var questionName = "qualityOverall"; // change this to formr name of the item
        var question = $("input[name=" + questionName + "]"); // the formr input field
        var slider = $("#" + questionName + "Range"); // the bootstrap slider
 
        question.hide(); // hide the number field
        slider.appendTo(question.parent()); // move slider to the correct column
        slider.slider(); // initiate the bootstrap slider
        slider.on("change", function(slideEvt) {
                //console.log("change event");
                question.val(slideEvt.value.newValue); // fill the value into the formr number field
                $(question.parent()).find(".slider-handle").css("display","block"); // make the handle visible
        });
     });
</script>

<script> 
     $(document).ready ( function() {
        var questionName = "qualityOverall"; // change this to formr name of the item
        var question = $("input[name=" + questionName + "]"); // the formr input field
        var slider = $("#" + questionName + "Range"); // the bootstrap slider
 
        question.hide(); // hide the number field
        slider.appendTo(question.parent()); // move slider to the correct column
        slider.slider(); // initiate the bootstrap slider
        slider.on("change", function(slideEvt) {
                //console.log("change event");
                question.val(slideEvt.value.newValue); // fill the value into the formr number field
                $(question.parent()).find(".slider-handle").css("display","block"); // make the handle visible
        });
     });
</script>

units.body:
All Experience Recaps are done!

You will soon be invited to do the conclusion questionnaire.


The Conclusion Questionnaire will automatically show up in this window, so you can keep this window open or close it until the invitation e-mail.

units.subject: Conclusion Questionnaire and Payment
units.body:
`r sample(c("Hi","Hey","Hello","Good morning"), 1, replace=TRUE)` `r AOTM_Eligibility$name`, You have reached the end of the daily recaps. There is only the conclusion questionnaire left for which we said you will earn 2 Euro. We realized now that the post-test takes a bit longer than we previously thought. We will, therefore, increase your payment to 4 Euro. It will still only take about 20 minutes. Really, we timed it :-) Once you have completed the conclusion questionnaire, you will receive your payment for the last 30 days.
To the conclusion questionnaire
Please make sure to follow the link as soon as possible. Thanks again for all your amazing work, The International Experience Study Team

choices.2: **B:** I am uncomfortable getting close to others. I want emotionally close relationships, but I find it difficult to trust others completely, or to depend on them. I worry that I will be hurt if I allow myself to become too close to others.
choices.3: **C:** I want to be completely emotionally intimate with others, but I often find that others are reluctant to get as close as I would like. I am uncomfortable being without close relationships, but I sometimes worry that others don’t value me as much as I value them.
choices.4: **D:** I am comfortable without close emotional relationships. It is very important to me to feel independent and self-sufficient, and I prefer not to depend on others or have others depend on me.

items.name: feedback
items.label:
## Your Personal Feedback Dashboard
**Below you can see your responses. Keep in mind that only you have access to this screen and no other person can see what you are seeing. If you decide to continue with the study, we will update your feedback every day. Also if there are any variables you would be especially interested in feel free to write us an e-mail and we will include them in the daily feedback.**
### Your Interactions
Over the past `r as.numeric(as.Date(Sys.Date())-as.Date(AOTM_Pre$ended))-1` days you reported on `r length(na.omit(AOTM_Daily$ended))` Interactions. The following graph shows you what types of interactions you entered: ```{r echo=FALSE, message=FALSE, warning=FALSE} #install.packages("htmlwidgets") library(htmlwidgets) library(highcharter) library(RColorBrewer) library(readr) library(dplyr) Interaction <- as.data.frame(table(AOTM_Daily %>% filter(!is.na(ended)) %>% select(Interaction))) names(Interaction) <- c("Type", "Frequency") highcharter::highchart() %>% hc_chart(type = "column") %>% hc_xAxis(categories = names(Interaction)) %>% hc_add_series(name = "Dutch", data = Interaction %>% filter(Type=="Dutch") %>% select(Frequency) %>% as.numeric()) %>% hc_add_series(name = "Non-Dutch", data = Interaction %>% filter(Type=="Non-Dutch") %>% select(Frequency) %>% as.numeric()) %>% hc_add_series(name = "No Interaction", data = Interaction %>% filter(Type=="no interaction") %>% select(Frequency) %>% as.numeric()) %>% hc_title(text = "Your Interactions")%>% hc_colors(brewer.pal(3, "Set2")) ```
###Your Well-Being
At every Recap you reported your general well-being (from very negative to very positve; the slider with the sad to happy smiley). Below you can find a graph that illustrates how your well-being changed over the course of the past `r as.numeric(as.Date(Sys.Date())-as.Date(AOTM_Pre$ended))-1` days. ```{r echo=FALSE, message=FALSE, warning=FALSE} FeedbackDaily <- AOTM_Daily %>% filter(!is.na(ended)) %>% select(ended, exWB, energy, afraid, angry, Autonomy, Competence, RelatednessOther, RelatednessSelf, RelatednessNoInteraction, AttitudesDutch) FeedbackDaily$dateTime <- as.POSIXct(FeedbackDaily$ended) FeedbackDaily$RelatednessNoInteractionRev <- FeedbackDaily$RelatednessNoInteraction*-1+100 FeedbackDaily$Relatedness <- rowMeans(FeedbackDaily %>% select(RelatednessOther, RelatednessSelf, RelatednessNoInteractionRev), na.rm = T) highcharter::highchart(type = "stock") %>% hc_chart(type = "line", zoomType = "x") %>% #hc_title(text = "Your Well-Being") %>% hc_xAxis(type = "datetime") %>% hc_yAxis(title = list(text = "Well-Being"), min = -100, max = 100, showLastLabel = T, showFirstLabel = T, plotLines = list( list(label = list(text = "Neutral"), color = "#'FF0000", width = 2, value = 0), list(label = list(text = "Negative"), color = "#'FF0000", width = 2, value = -100), list(label = list(text = "Positive"), color = "#'FF0000", width = 2, value = 100))) %>% hc_plotOptions(line = list( dataLabels = list(enabled = F), enableMouseTracking = TRUE) ) %>% hc_add_series(FeedbackDaily, "spline", hcaes(datetime_to_timestamp(dateTime), exWB), name="Well-Being", marker = list(enabled = TRUE, radius=3))%>% hc_rangeSelector( verticalAlign = "top", buttons = list( list(type = 'all', text = 'All'), list(type = 'day', count = 14, text = '14d'), list(type = 'day', count = 7, text = '7d'), list(type = 'hour', count = 48, text = '48h'), list(type = 'hour', count = 24, text = '24h') )) ``` Note: You can hover over the line to see the exact values. You can focus on a specific time period by using the zoom buttons and the 'From'-'To' fields above the graph, the range selector below the graph or by simply selecting a range within the graph with your mouse or finger (click and drag).
###Your Mood
At every Recap you also reported your emotional state of worry, anger and your enery levels. Below you can find a graph that illustrates how your states changed over the course of the past `r as.numeric(as.Date(Sys.Date())-as.Date(AOTM_Pre$ended))-1` days. ```{r echo=FALSE, message=FALSE, warning=FALSE} highcharter::highchart(type = "stock") %>% hc_chart(type = "line", zoomType = "x") %>% #hc_title(text = "Your Mood") %>% hc_xAxis(type = "datetime") %>% hc_yAxis(title = list(text = "Mood"), min = 0, max = 100, showLastLabel = T, showFirstLabel = T, opposite = TRUE, plotLines = list( list(label = list(text = "not at all"), color = "#'FF0000", width = 2, value = 0), list(label = list(text = "A great deal"), color = "#'FF0000", width = 2, value = 100))) %>% hc_add_series(FeedbackDaily, "spline", hcaes(datetime_to_timestamp(dateTime), energy), name="Energy", showInNavigator = TRUE, marker = list(enabled = TRUE, radius=3, symbol = "circle"))%>% hc_add_series(FeedbackDaily, "spline", hcaes(datetime_to_timestamp(dateTime), afraid), name="Worry", showInNavigator = TRUE, marker = list(enabled = TRUE, radius=3, symbol = "circle"))%>% hc_add_series(FeedbackDaily, "spline", hcaes(datetime_to_timestamp(dateTime), angry), name="Anger", showInNavigator = TRUE, marker = list(enabled = TRUE, radius=3, symbol = "circle"))%>% hc_colors(brewer.pal(3, "Set1"))%>% hc_legend(enabled = TRUE)%>% hc_plotOptions( line = list( dataLabels = list(enabled = F), enableMouseTracking = TRUE, showInNavigator = TRUE) )%>% hc_rangeSelector( verticalAlign = "top", buttons = list( list(type = 'all', text = 'All'), list(type = 'day', count = 14, text = '14d'), list(type = 'day', count = 7, text = '7d'), list(type = 'hour', count = 48, text = '48h'), list(type = 'hour', count = 24, text = '24h') )) ``` Note: You can hide or display lines by selecting and de-selecting them in the legend below the graph. You can also hover over the lines to see the exact values. You can focus on a specific time period by using the zoom buttons and the 'From'-'To' fields above the graph, the range selector below the graph or by simply selecting a range within the graph with your mouse or finger (click and drag).
###Your Psychological Needs
There is a growing body of literature assuming that humans have three basic psychological needs (e.g., Deci and Ryan, 2008). (1) The need to have an impact on the self or one's environment (need for competence), (2) the need to experience a sense of choice and psychological freedom in everyday life (need for autonomy), and (3) the need to care about and be cared about by others (need to belong). Over the past `r as.numeric(as.Date(Sys.Date())-as.Date(AOTM_Pre$ended))-1` days we asked you to report how much these three needs were fulfilled during your interactions or your everyday life. Below you can see how your three needs (co-)developed over time. ```{r echo=FALSE, message=FALSE, warning=FALSE} highcharter::highchart(type = "stock") %>% hc_chart(type = "line", zoomType = "x") %>% #hc_title(text = "Your Mood") %>% hc_xAxis(type = "datetime") %>% hc_yAxis(title = list(text = "Mood"), min = 0, max = 100, showLastLabel = T, showFirstLabel = T, opposite = TRUE, plotLines = list( list(label = list(text = "not at all"), color = "#'FF0000", width = 2, value = 0), list(label = list(text = "A great deal"), color = "#'FF0000", width = 2, value = 100))) %>% hc_add_series(FeedbackDaily, "spline", hcaes(datetime_to_timestamp(dateTime), Autonomy), name="Autonomy", showInNavigator = TRUE, marker = list(enabled = TRUE, radius=3, symbol = "circle"))%>% hc_add_series(FeedbackDaily, "spline", hcaes(datetime_to_timestamp(dateTime), Competence), name="Competence", showInNavigator = TRUE, marker = list(enabled = TRUE, radius=3, symbol = "circle"))%>% hc_add_series(FeedbackDaily, "spline", showInNavigator = TRUE, hcaes(datetime_to_timestamp(dateTime), Relatedness), name="Relatedness", marker = list(enabled = TRUE, radius=3, symbol = "circle"))%>% hc_colors(brewer.pal(3, "Dark2"))%>% hc_legend(enabled = TRUE)%>% hc_plotOptions( line = list( dataLabels = list(enabled = F), enableMouseTracking = TRUE, showInNavigator = TRUE) )%>% hc_rangeSelector( verticalAlign = "top", buttons = list( list(type = 'all', text = 'All'), list(type = 'day', count = 14, text = '14d'), list(type = 'day', count = 7, text = '7d'), list(type = 'hour', count = 48, text = '48h'), list(type = 'hour', count = 24, text = '24h') )) ``` Note: You can hide or display lines by selecting and de-selecting them in the legend below the graph. You can also hover over the lines to see the exact values. You can focus on a specific time period by using the zoom buttons and the 'From'-'To' fields above the graph, the range selector below the graph or by simply selecting a range within the graph with your mouse or finger (click and drag).
###Your Attitudes towards the Dutch
Towards the end of every Recap you reported how you feel towards the Dutch (i.e., the feeling thermometer). Below you can find a graph that illustrates how your feelings towards the Dutch changed over the past `r as.numeric(as.Date(Sys.Date())-as.Date(AOTM_Pre$ended))-1` days. ```{r echo=FALSE, message=FALSE, warning=FALSE} highcharter::highchart(type = "stock") %>% hc_chart(type = "line", zoomType = "x") %>% #hc_title(text = "Your Attitudes towards the Dutch") %>% hc_xAxis(type = "datetime") %>% hc_yAxis(title = list(text = "Feeling Thermometer Dutch"), min = 0, max = 100, showLastLabel = T, showFirstLabel = T, labels = list(format = "{value}°"), plotLines = list( list(label = list(text = "very cold"), color = "#'FF0000", width = 2, value = 0), list(label = list(text = "neutral"), color = "#'FF0000", width = 2, value = 50), list(label = list(text = "very warm"), color = "#'FF0000", width = 2, value = 100))) %>% hc_plotOptions(line = list( dataLabels = list(enabled = F), enableMouseTracking = TRUE) ) %>% hc_add_series(FeedbackDaily, "spline", hcaes(datetime_to_timestamp(dateTime), AttitudesDutch), name="Feeling", color = "darkred", marker = list(enabled = TRUE, radius=3))%>% hc_rangeSelector( verticalAlign = "top", buttons = list( list(type = 'all', text = 'All'), list(type = 'day', count = 14, text = '14d'), list(type = 'day', count = 7, text = '7d'), list(type = 'hour', count = 48, text = '48h'), list(type = 'hour', count = 24, text = '24h') )) ``` Note: You can hover over the line to see the exact values. You can focus on a specific time period by using the zoom buttons and the 'From'-'To' fields above the graph, the range selector below the graph or by simply selecting a range within the graph with your mouse or finger (click and drag).

This would earn you an additional", 60-length(na.omit(AOTM_Daily$ended)), "€."))` You already earned `r sum(na.omit(AOTM_Daily$ended) > AOTM_Post$ended)` € by continuing with the study.


Your Personal Feedback Dashboard

Also, if there are any variables you would be especially interested in feel free to write us an e-mail and we will include them in the daily feedback (j.kreienkap@rug.nl/ m.agostini@rug.nl).**

Your Interactions

Over the past `r as.numeric(as.Date(Sys.Date())-as.Date(AOTM_Pre$ended))-1` days you reported on `r length(na.omit(AOTM_Daily$ended))` Interactions. The following graph shows you what types of interactions you entered: ```{r echo=FALSE, message=FALSE, warning=FALSE} #install.packages("htmlwidgets") library(htmlwidgets) library(highcharter) library(RColorBrewer) library(readr) library(dplyr) Interaction <- as.data.frame(table(AOTM_Daily %>% filter(!is.na(ended)) %>% select(Interaction))) names(Interaction) <- c("Type", "Frequency") highcharter::highchart() %>% hc_chart(type = "column") %>% hc_xAxis(categories = names(Interaction)) %>% hc_add_series(name = "Dutch", data = Interaction %>% filter(Type=="Dutch") %>% select(Frequency) %>% as.numeric()) %>% hc_add_series(name = "Non-Dutch", data = Interaction %>% filter(Type=="Non-Dutch") %>% select(Frequency) %>% as.numeric()) %>% hc_add_series(name = "No Interaction", data = Interaction %>% filter(Type=="no interaction") %>% select(Frequency) %>% as.numeric()) %>% #hc_title(text = "Your Interactions")%>% hc_colors(brewer.pal(3, "Set2")) ```

Your Well-Being

At every Recap you reported your general well-being (from very negative to very positve; the slider with the sad to happy smiley). Below you can find a graph that illustrates how your well-being changed over the course of the past `r as.numeric(as.Date(Sys.Date())-as.Date(AOTM_Pre$ended))-1` days. ```{r echo=FALSE, message=FALSE, warning=FALSE} FeedbackDaily <- AOTM_Daily %>% filter(!is.na(ended)) %>% select(ended, exWB, energy, afraid, angry, Autonomy, Competence, RelatednessOther, RelatednessSelf, RelatednessNoInteraction, AttitudesDutch, Interaction, StudentGoal01, StudentGoal02, StudentGoal03, StudentGoal04, StudentGoal05, StudentGoal06, StudentGoal07, StudentGoal08, StudentGoal09, StudentGoal10) FeedbackDaily$dateTime <- as.POSIXct(FeedbackDaily$ended) FeedbackDaily$RelatednessNoInteractionRev <- FeedbackDaily$RelatednessNoInteraction*-1+100 FeedbackDaily$Relatedness <- rowMeans(FeedbackDaily %>% select(RelatednessOther, RelatednessSelf, RelatednessNoInteractionRev), na.rm = T) highcharter::highchart(type = "stock") %>% hc_chart(type = "line", zoomType = "x") %>% #hc_title(text = "Your Well-Being") %>% hc_xAxis(type = "datetime") %>% hc_yAxis(title = list(text = "Well-Being"), min = -100, max = 100, showLastLabel = T, showFirstLabel = T, plotLines = list( list(label = list(text = "Neutral"), color = "#'FF0000", width = 2, value = 0), list(label = list(text = "Negative"), color = "#'FF0000", width = 2, value = -100), list(label = list(text = "Positive"), color = "#'FF0000", width = 2, value = 100))) %>% hc_plotOptions(line = list( dataLabels = list(enabled = F), enableMouseTracking = TRUE) ) %>% hc_add_series(FeedbackDaily, "spline", hcaes(datetime_to_timestamp(dateTime), exWB), name="Well-Being", marker = list(enabled = TRUE, radius=3))%>% hc_rangeSelector( verticalAlign = "top", buttons = list( list(type = 'all', text = 'All'), list(type = 'day', count = 14, text = '14d'), list(type = 'day', count = 7, text = '7d'), list(type = 'hour', count = 48, text = '48h'), list(type = 'hour', count = 24, text = '24h') )) ``` Note: You can hover over the line to see the exact values. You can focus on a specific time period by using the zoom buttons and the 'From'-'To' fields above the graph, the range selector below the graph or by simply selecting a range within the graph with your mouse or finger (click and drag).

Your Mood

At every Recap you also reported your emotional state of worry, anger and your enery levels. Below you can find a graph that illustrates how your states changed over the course of the past `r as.numeric(as.Date(Sys.Date())-as.Date(AOTM_Pre$ended))-1` days. ```{r echo=FALSE, message=FALSE, warning=FALSE} highcharter::highchart(type = "stock") %>% hc_chart(type = "line", zoomType = "x") %>% #hc_title(text = "Your Mood") %>% hc_xAxis(type = "datetime") %>% hc_yAxis(title = list(text = "Mood"), min = 0, max = 100, showLastLabel = T, showFirstLabel = T, opposite = TRUE, plotLines = list( list(label = list(text = "not at all"), color = "#'FF0000", width = 2, value = 0), list(label = list(text = "A great deal"), color = "#'FF0000", width = 2, value = 100))) %>% hc_add_series(FeedbackDaily, "spline", hcaes(datetime_to_timestamp(dateTime), energy), name="Energy", showInNavigator = TRUE, marker = list(enabled = TRUE, radius=3, symbol = "circle"))%>% hc_add_series(FeedbackDaily, "spline", hcaes(datetime_to_timestamp(dateTime), afraid), name="Worry", showInNavigator = TRUE, marker = list(enabled = TRUE, radius=3, symbol = "circle"))%>% hc_add_series(FeedbackDaily, "spline", hcaes(datetime_to_timestamp(dateTime), angry), name="Anger", showInNavigator = TRUE, marker = list(enabled = TRUE, radius=3, symbol = "circle"))%>% hc_colors(brewer.pal(3, "Set1"))%>% hc_legend(enabled = TRUE)%>% hc_plotOptions( line = list( dataLabels = list(enabled = F), enableMouseTracking = TRUE, showInNavigator = TRUE) )%>% hc_rangeSelector( verticalAlign = "top", buttons = list( list(type = 'all', text = 'All'), list(type = 'day', count = 14, text = '14d'), list(type = 'day', count = 7, text = '7d'), list(type = 'hour', count = 48, text = '48h'), list(type = 'hour', count = 24, text = '24h') )) ``` Note: You can hide or display lines by selecting and de-selecting them in the legend below the graph. Your Psychological Needs

There is a growing body of literature assuming that humans have three basic psychological needs (e.g., Deci and Ryan, 2008). (1) The need to have an impact on the self or one's environment (need for competence), (2) the need to experience a sense of choice and psychological freedom in everyday life (need for autonomy), and (3) the need to care about and be cared about by others (need to belong). Over the past `r as.numeric(as.Date(Sys.Date())-as.Date(AOTM_Pre$ended))-1` days we asked you to report how much these three needs were fulfilled during your interactions or your everyday life. Below you can see how your three needs (co-)developed over time. Please keep in mind that the need to belong can vary quite strongly depending on whether you had an interaction or not. ```{r echo=FALSE, message=FALSE, warning=FALSE} highcharter::highchart(type = "stock") %>% hc_chart(type = "line", zoomType = "x") %>% #hc_title(text = "Your Mood") %>% hc_xAxis(type = "datetime") %>% hc_yAxis(title = list(text = "Mood"), min = 0, max = 100, showLastLabel = T, showFirstLabel = T, opposite = TRUE, plotLines = list( list(label = list(text = "not at all"), color = "#'FF0000", width = 2, value = 0), list(label = list(text = "A great deal"), color = "#'FF0000", width = 2, value = 100))) %>% hc_add_series(FeedbackDaily, "spline", hcaes(x = datetime_to_timestamp(dateTime), y = Autonomy), name="Autonomy", showInNavigator = TRUE, marker = list(enabled = TRUE, radius=3, symbol = "circle"))%>% hc_add_series(FeedbackDaily, "spline", hcaes(datetime_to_timestamp(dateTime), Competence), name="Competence", showInNavigator = TRUE, marker = list(enabled = TRUE, radius=3, symbol = "circle"))%>% hc_add_series(FeedbackDaily, "spline", showInNavigator = TRUE, hcaes(datetime_to_timestamp(dateTime), Relatedness), name="Relatedness", marker = list(enabled = TRUE, radius=3, symbol = "circle"))%>% hc_colors(brewer.pal(3, "Dark2"))%>% hc_legend(enabled = TRUE)%>% hc_plotOptions( line = list( dataLabels = list(enabled = F), enableMouseTracking = TRUE, showInNavigator = TRUE) )%>% hc_rangeSelector( verticalAlign = "top", buttons = list( list(type = 'all', text = 'All'), list(type = 'day', count = 14, text = '14d'), list(type = 'day', count = 7, text = '7d'), list(type = 'hour', count = 48, text = '48h'), list(type = 'hour', count = 24, text = '24h') )) ``` Note: You can hide or display lines by selecting and de-selecting them in the legend below the graph. You can also hover over the lines to see the exact values. You can focus on a specific time period by using the zoom buttons and the 'From'-'To' fields above the graph, the range selector below the graph or by simply selecting a range within the graph with your mouse or finger (click and drag).

Your Daily Goals

Every day we asked you how important different goals were to you. The following graph illustrated how your daily goals changed over the course of this study. To not overwhelm you only one is active but you can click on the legend to see your other goals. ```{r echo=FALSE, message=FALSE, warning=FALSE} randStGoal <- sample(c("TRUE", "FALSE", "FALSE", "FALSE", "FALSE", "FALSE", "FALSE", "FALSE", "FALSE", "FALSE")) highcharter::highchart(type = "stock") %>% hc_chart(type = "line", zoomType = "x") %>% #hc_title(text = "Your Mood") %>% hc_xAxis(type = "datetime") %>% hc_yAxis(title = list(text = "Mood"), min = 0, max = 100, showLastLabel = T, showFirstLabel = T, opposite = TRUE, plotLines = list( list(label = list(text = "Not important"), color = "#'FF0000", width = 2, value = 0), list(label = list(text = "Very important"), color = "#'FF0000", width = 2, value = 100))) %>% hc_add_series(FeedbackDaily, "spline", hcaes(x = datetime_to_timestamp(dateTime), y = StudentGoal01), name=c("Social Support Goal"), showInNavigator = TRUE, visible = as.logical(randStGoal[1]), marker = list(enabled = TRUE, radius=3, symbol = "circle"))%>% hc_add_series(FeedbackDaily, "spline", hcaes(x = datetime_to_timestamp(dateTime), y = StudentGoal02), name=c("Romantic Goal"), showInNavigator = TRUE, visible = as.logical(randStGoal[2]), marker = list(enabled = TRUE, radius=3, symbol = "circle"))%>% hc_add_series(FeedbackDaily, "spline", hcaes(x = datetime_to_timestamp(dateTime), y = StudentGoal03), name=c("Academic Goal"), showInNavigator = TRUE, visible = as.logical(randStGoal[3]), marker = list(enabled = TRUE, radius=3, symbol = "circle"))%>% hc_add_series(FeedbackDaily, "spline", hcaes(x = datetime_to_timestamp(dateTime), y = StudentGoal04), name=c("Career Goal"), showInNavigator = TRUE, visible = as.logical(randStGoal[4]), marker = list(enabled = TRUE, radius=3, symbol = "circle"))%>% hc_add_series(FeedbackDaily, "spline", hcaes(x = datetime_to_timestamp(dateTime), y = StudentGoal05), name=c("Financial Goal"), showInNavigator = TRUE, visible = as.logical(randStGoal[5]), marker = list(enabled = TRUE, radius=3, symbol = "circle"))%>% hc_add_series(FeedbackDaily, "spline", hcaes(x = datetime_to_timestamp(dateTime), y = StudentGoal06), name=c("Health Goal"), showInNavigator = TRUE, visible = as.logical(randStGoal[6]), marker = list(enabled = TRUE, radius=3, symbol = "circle"))%>% hc_add_series(FeedbackDaily, "spline", hcaes(x = datetime_to_timestamp(dateTime), y = StudentGoal07), name=c("Leisure Goal"), showInNavigator = TRUE, visible = as.logical(randStGoal[7]), marker = list(enabled = TRUE, radius=3, symbol = "circle"))%>% hc_add_series(FeedbackDaily, "spline", hcaes(x = datetime_to_timestamp(dateTime), y = StudentGoal08), name=c("Personal Improvement Goal"), showInNavigator = TRUE, visible = as.logical(randStGoal[8]), marker = list(enabled = TRUE, radius=3, symbol = "circle"))%>% hc_add_series(FeedbackDaily, "spline", hcaes(x = datetime_to_timestamp(dateTime), y = StudentGoal09), name=c("Helping Goal"), showInNavigator = TRUE, visible = as.logical(randStGoal[9]), marker = list(enabled = TRUE, radius=3, symbol = "circle"))%>% hc_add_series(FeedbackDaily, "spline", hcaes(x = datetime_to_timestamp(dateTime), y = StudentGoal10), name=c("Spiritual Goal"), showInNavigator = TRUE, visible = as.logical(randStGoal[10]), marker = list(enabled = TRUE, radius=3, symbol = "circle"))%>% hc_colors(brewer.pal(10, "Dark2"))%>% hc_legend(enabled = TRUE)%>% hc_plotOptions( line = list( dataLabels = list(enabled = F), enableMouseTracking = TRUE, showInNavigator = TRUE) )%>% hc_rangeSelector( verticalAlign = "top", buttons = list( list(type = 'all', text = 'All'), list(type = 'day', count = 14, text = '14d'), list(type = 'day', count = 7, text = '7d'), list(type = 'hour', count = 48, text = '48h'), list(type = 'hour', count = 24, text = '24h') )) ``` Note: You can hide or display lines by selecting and de-selecting them in the legend below the graph. You can also hover over the lines to see the exact values. You can focus on a specific time period by using the zoom buttons and the 'From'-'To' fields above the graph, the range selector below the graph or by simply selecting a range within the graph with your mouse or finger (click and drag).

Your Attitudes towards the Dutch

Towards the end of every Recap you reported how you feel towards the Dutch (i.e., the feeling thermometer). Below you can find a graph that illustrates how your feelings towards the Dutch changed over the past `r as.numeric(as.Date(Sys.Date())-as.Date(AOTM_Pre$ended))-1` days. ```{r echo=FALSE, message=FALSE, warning=FALSE} highcharter::highchart(type = "stock") %>% hc_chart(type = "line", zoomType = "x") %>% #hc_title(text = "Your Attitudes towards the Dutch") %>% hc_xAxis(type = "datetime") %>% hc_yAxis(title = list(text = "Feeling Thermometer Dutch"), min = 0, max = 100, showLastLabel = T, showFirstLabel = T, labels = list(format = "{value}°"), plotLines = list( list(label = list(text = "very cold"), color = "#'FF0000", width = 2, value = 0), list(label = list(text = "neutral"), color = "#'FF0000", width = 2, value = 50), list(label = list(text = "very warm"), color = "#'FF0000", width = 2, value = 100))) %>% hc_plotOptions(line = list( dataLabels = list(enabled = F), enableMouseTracking = TRUE) ) %>% hc_add_series(FeedbackDaily, "spline", hcaes(datetime_to_timestamp(dateTime), AttitudesDutch), name="Feeling", color = "darkred", marker = list(enabled = TRUE, radius=3))%>% hc_rangeSelector( verticalAlign = "top", buttons = list( list(type = 'all', text = 'All'), list(type = 'day', count = 14, text = '14d'), list(type = 'day', count = 7, text = '7d'), list(type = 'hour', count = 48, text = '48h'), list(type = 'hour', count = 24, text = '24h') )) ``` Note: You can hover over the line to see the exact values. You can focus on a specific time period by using the zoom buttons and the 'From'-'To' fields above the graph, the range selector below the graph or by simply selecting a range within the graph with your mouse or finger (click and drag).

Your Personality

In the post-questionnaire we asked you a few short questions related to your personality. Below you can see a plot that represents those personality scores. If you are interested in learning more about them, check out: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_Five_personality_traits ```{r echo=FALSE, message=FALSE, warning=FALSE} library(radarchart) extraversion <- mean(c(AOTM_Post$bigFive01*-1+6, AOTM_Post$bigFive06)) agreeableness <- mean(c(AOTM_Post$bigFive07*-1+6, AOTM_Post$bigFive02)) conscientiousness <- mean(c(AOTM_Post$bigFive03*-1+6, AOTM_Post$bigFive08)) neuroticism <- mean(c(AOTM_Post$bigFive04*-1+6, AOTM_Post$bigFive09)) openness <- mean(c(AOTM_Post$bigFive05*-1+6, AOTM_Post$bigFive10)) labs <- c("Openness", "Conscientiousness", "Extraversion", "Agreeableness", "Neuroticism") scores <- list( "You" = c(openness, conscientiousness, extraversion, agreeableness, neuroticism) ) radarchart::chartJSRadar(scores = scores, labs = labs, maxScale = 5) ```

The next Recap will automatically show up in this window, so you can keep this window open or close it until the next invitation e-mail.

units.subject: Morning Recap
units.body:
`r sample(c("Hi","Hey","Good afternoon","Hello"), 1, replace=TRUE)` `r AOTM_Eligibility$name`, Your morning Experience Recap for `r format(Sys.Date(),"%A %B %d")` is ready for you. Follow this link to the short Survey:
Start the Recap now
Please make sure to fill in the survey as soon as possible. It really just takes four to five minutes. (Keep in mind that this link expires at 18:30 o'clock) `r sample(c("All the best,","Best wishes,","Cheers,"), 1, replace=TRUE)` The International Experience Study Team

units.body:
Hey `r AOTM_Eligibility$name`, We are excited that you are still part of the study and look forward to your responses over the next `r 64-(as.numeric(as.Date(Sys.Date())-as.Date(AOTM_Pre$ended)))` days.   `r ifelse(60-length(na.omit(AOTM_Daily$ended))<1, paste("You filled out all the daily recaps. That is absolutely amazing! If you are interested in learning more about yourself, we would be excited if you continue filling out the daily questionnaires."), paste("You missed", 60-length(na.omit(AOTM_Daily$ended)), "daily recaps, which you could fill out over the following", 64-(as.numeric(as.Date(Sys.Date())-as.Date(AOTM_Pre$ended))), "days. This would earn you an additional", 60-length(na.omit(AOTM_Daily$ended)), "€."))` You already earned `r sum(na.omit(AOTM_Daily$ended) > AOTM_Post$ended)` € by continuing with the study.


Your Personal Feedback Dashboard

**Below you can see your responses. Keep in mind that only you have access to this screen and no other person can see what you are seeing. If you decide to continue with the study, we will update your feedback every day. Also, if there are any variables you would be especially interested in feel free to write us an e-mail and we will include them in the daily feedback (j.kreienkap@rug.nl/ m.agostini@rug.nl).**

Your Interactions

Over the past `r as.numeric(as.Date(Sys.Date())-as.Date(AOTM_Pre$ended))-1` days you reported on `r length(na.omit(AOTM_Daily$ended))` Interactions. The following graph shows you what types of interactions you entered: ```{r echo=FALSE, message=FALSE, warning=FALSE} #install.packages("htmlwidgets") library(htmlwidgets) library(highcharter) library(RColorBrewer) library(readr) library(dplyr) Interaction <- as.data.frame(table(AOTM_Daily %>% filter(!is.na(ended)) %>% select(Interaction))) names(Interaction) <- c("Type", "Frequency") highcharter::highchart() %>% hc_chart(type = "column") %>% hc_xAxis(categories = names(Interaction)) %>% hc_add_series(name = "Dutch", data = Interaction %>% filter(Type=="Dutch") %>% select(Frequency) %>% as.numeric()) %>% hc_add_series(name = "Non-Dutch", data = Interaction %>% filter(Type=="Non-Dutch") %>% select(Frequency) %>% as.numeric()) %>% hc_add_series(name = "No Interaction", data = Interaction %>% filter(Type=="no interaction") %>% select(Frequency) %>% as.numeric()) %>% #hc_title(text = "Your Interactions")%>% hc_colors(brewer.pal(3, "Set2")) ```

Your Well-Being

At every Recap you reported your general well-being (from very negative to very positve; the slider with the sad to happy smiley). Below you can find a graph that illustrates how your well-being changed over the course of the past `r as.numeric(as.Date(Sys.Date())-as.Date(AOTM_Pre$ended))-1` days. ```{r echo=FALSE, message=FALSE, warning=FALSE} FeedbackDaily <- AOTM_Daily %>% filter(!is.na(ended)) %>% select(ended, exWB, energy, afraid, angry, Autonomy, Competence, RelatednessOther, RelatednessSelf, RelatednessNoInteraction, AttitudesDutch, Interaction, StudentGoal01, StudentGoal02, StudentGoal03, StudentGoal04, StudentGoal05, StudentGoal06, StudentGoal07, StudentGoal08, StudentGoal09, StudentGoal10) FeedbackDaily$dateTime <- as.POSIXct(FeedbackDaily$ended) FeedbackDaily$RelatednessNoInteractionRev <- FeedbackDaily$RelatednessNoInteraction*-1+100 FeedbackDaily$Relatedness <- rowMeans(FeedbackDaily %>% select(RelatednessOther, RelatednessSelf, RelatednessNoInteractionRev), na.rm = T) highcharter::highchart(type = "stock") %>% hc_chart(type = "line", zoomType = "x") %>% #hc_title(text = "Your Well-Being") %>% hc_xAxis(type = "datetime") %>% hc_yAxis(title = list(text = "Well-Being"), min = -100, max = 100, showLastLabel = T, showFirstLabel = T, plotLines = list( list(label = list(text = "Neutral"), color = "#'FF0000", width = 2, value = 0), list(label = list(text = "Negative"), color = "#'FF0000", width = 2, value = -100), list(label = list(text = "Positive"), color = "#'FF0000", width = 2, value = 100))) %>% hc_plotOptions(line = list( dataLabels = list(enabled = F), enableMouseTracking = TRUE) ) %>% hc_add_series(FeedbackDaily, "spline", hcaes(datetime_to_timestamp(dateTime), exWB), name="Well-Being", marker = list(enabled = TRUE, radius=3))%>% hc_rangeSelector( verticalAlign = "top", buttons = list( list(type = 'all', text = 'All'), list(type = 'day', count = 14, text = '14d'), list(type = 'day', count = 7, text = '7d'), list(type = 'hour', count = 48, text = '48h'), list(type = 'hour', count = 24, text = '24h') )) ``` Note: You can hover over the line to see the exact values. You can focus on a specific time period by using the zoom buttons and the 'From'-'To' fields above the graph, the range selector below the graph or by simply selecting a range within the graph with your mouse or finger (click and drag).

Your Mood

At every Recap you also reported your emotional state of worry, anger and your enery levels. Below you can find a graph that illustrates how your states changed over the course of the past `r as.numeric(as.Date(Sys.Date())-as.Date(AOTM_Pre$ended))-1` days. ```{r echo=FALSE, message=FALSE, warning=FALSE} highcharter::highchart(type = "stock") %>% hc_chart(type = "line", zoomType = "x") %>% #hc_title(text = "Your Mood") %>% hc_xAxis(type = "datetime") %>% hc_yAxis(title = list(text = "Mood"), min = 0, max = 100, showLastLabel = T, showFirstLabel = T, opposite = TRUE, plotLines = list( list(label = list(text = "not at all"), color = "#'FF0000", width = 2, value = 0), list(label = list(text = "A great deal"), color = "#'FF0000", width = 2, value = 100))) %>% hc_add_series(FeedbackDaily, "spline", hcaes(datetime_to_timestamp(dateTime), energy), name="Energy", showInNavigator = TRUE, marker = list(enabled = TRUE, radius=3, symbol = "circle"))%>% hc_add_series(FeedbackDaily, "spline", hcaes(datetime_to_timestamp(dateTime), afraid), name="Worry", showInNavigator = TRUE, marker = list(enabled = TRUE, radius=3, symbol = "circle"))%>% hc_add_series(FeedbackDaily, "spline", hcaes(datetime_to_timestamp(dateTime), angry), name="Anger", showInNavigator = TRUE, marker = list(enabled = TRUE, radius=3, symbol = "circle"))%>% hc_colors(brewer.pal(3, "Set1"))%>% hc_legend(enabled = TRUE)%>% hc_plotOptions( line = list( dataLabels = list(enabled = F), enableMouseTracking = TRUE, showInNavigator = TRUE) )%>% hc_rangeSelector( verticalAlign = "top", buttons = list( list(type = 'all', text = 'All'), list(type = 'day', count = 14, text = '14d'), list(type = 'day', count = 7, text = '7d'), list(type = 'hour', count = 48, text = '48h'), list(type = 'hour', count = 24, text = '24h') )) ``` Note: You can hide or display lines by selecting and de-selecting them in the legend below the graph. You can also hover over the lines to see the exact values. You can focus on a specific time period by using the zoom buttons and the 'From'-'To' fields above the graph, the range selector below the graph or by simply selecting a range within the graph with your mouse or finger (click and drag).

Your Psychological Needs

There is a growing body of literature assuming that humans have three basic psychological needs (e.g., Deci and Ryan, 2008). (1) The need to have an impact on the self or one's environment (need for competence), (2) the need to experience a sense of choice and psychological freedom in everyday life (need for autonomy), and (3) the need to care about and be cared about by others (need to belong). Over the past `r as.numeric(as.Date(Sys.Date())-as.Date(AOTM_Pre$ended))-1` days we asked you to report how much these three needs were fulfilled during your interactions or your everyday life. Below you can see how your three needs (co-)developed over time. Please keep in mind that the need to belong can vary quite strongly depending on whether you had an interaction or not. ```{r echo=FALSE, message=FALSE, warning=FALSE} highcharter::highchart(type = "stock") %>% hc_chart(type = "line", zoomType = "x") %>% #hc_title(text = "Your Mood") %>% hc_xAxis(type = "datetime") %>% hc_yAxis(title = list(text = "Mood"), min = 0, max = 100, showLastLabel = T, showFirstLabel = T, opposite = TRUE, plotLines = list( list(label = list(text = "not at all"), color = "#'FF0000", width = 2, value = 0), list(label = list(text = "A great deal"), color = "#'FF0000", width = 2, value = 100))) %>% hc_add_series(FeedbackDaily, "spline", hcaes(x = datetime_to_timestamp(dateTime), y = Autonomy), name="Autonomy", showInNavigator = TRUE, marker = list(enabled = TRUE, radius=3, symbol = "circle"))%>% hc_add_series(FeedbackDaily, "spline", hcaes(datetime_to_timestamp(dateTime), Competence), name="Competence", showInNavigator = TRUE, marker = list(enabled = TRUE, radius=3, symbol = "circle"))%>% hc_add_series(FeedbackDaily, "spline", showInNavigator = TRUE, hcaes(datetime_to_timestamp(dateTime), Relatedness), name="Relatedness", marker = list(enabled = TRUE, radius=3, symbol = "circle"))%>% hc_colors(brewer.pal(3, "Dark2"))%>% hc_legend(enabled = TRUE)%>% hc_plotOptions( line = list( dataLabels = list(enabled = F), enableMouseTracking = TRUE, showInNavigator = TRUE) )%>% hc_rangeSelector( verticalAlign = "top", buttons = list( list(type = 'all', text = 'All'), list(type = 'day', count = 14, text = '14d'), list(type = 'day', count = 7, text = '7d'), list(type = 'hour', count = 48, text = '48h'), list(type = 'hour', count = 24, text = '24h') )) ``` Note: You can hide or display lines by selecting and de-selecting them in the legend below the graph. You can also hover over the lines to see the exact values. You can focus on a specific time period by using the zoom buttons and the 'From'-'To' fields above the graph, the range selector below the graph or by simply selecting a range within the graph with your mouse or finger (click and drag).

Your Daily Goals

Every day we asked you how important different goals were to you. The following graph illustrated how your daily goals changed over the course of this study. To not overwhelm you only one is active but you can click on the legend to see your other goals. ```{r echo=FALSE, message=FALSE, warning=FALSE} randStGoal <- sample(c("TRUE", "FALSE", "FALSE", "FALSE", "FALSE", "FALSE", "FALSE", "FALSE", "FALSE", "FALSE")) highcharter::highchart(type = "stock") %>% hc_chart(type = "line", zoomType = "x") %>% #hc_title(text = "Your Mood") %>% hc_xAxis(type = "datetime") %>% hc_yAxis(title = list(text = "Mood"), min = 0, max = 100, showLastLabel = T, showFirstLabel = T, opposite = TRUE, plotLines = list( list(label = list(text = "Not important"), color = "#'FF0000", width = 2, value = 0), list(label = list(text = "Very important"), color = "#'FF0000", width = 2, value = 100))) %>% hc_add_series(FeedbackDaily, "spline", hcaes(x = datetime_to_timestamp(dateTime), y = StudentGoal01), name=c("Social Support Goal"), showInNavigator = TRUE, visible = as.logical(randStGoal[1]), marker = list(enabled = TRUE, radius=3, symbol = "circle"))%>% hc_add_series(FeedbackDaily, "spline", hcaes(x = datetime_to_timestamp(dateTime), y = StudentGoal02), name=c("Romantic Goal"), showInNavigator = TRUE, visible = as.logical(randStGoal[2]), marker = list(enabled = TRUE, radius=3, symbol = "circle"))%>% hc_add_series(FeedbackDaily, "spline", hcaes(x = datetime_to_timestamp(dateTime), y = StudentGoal03), name=c("Academic Goal"), showInNavigator = TRUE, visible = as.logical(randStGoal[3]), marker = list(enabled = TRUE, radius=3, symbol = "circle"))%>% hc_add_series(FeedbackDaily, "spline", hcaes(x = datetime_to_timestamp(dateTime), y = StudentGoal04), name=c("Career Goal"), showInNavigator = TRUE, visible = as.logical(randStGoal[4]), marker = list(enabled = TRUE, radius=3, symbol = "circle"))%>% hc_add_series(FeedbackDaily, "spline", hcaes(x = datetime_to_timestamp(dateTime), y = StudentGoal05), name=c("Financial Goal"), showInNavigator = TRUE, visible = as.logical(randStGoal[5]), marker = list(enabled = TRUE, radius=3, symbol = "circle"))%>% hc_add_series(FeedbackDaily, "spline", hcaes(x = datetime_to_timestamp(dateTime), y = StudentGoal06), name=c("Health Goal"), showInNavigator = TRUE, visible = as.logical(randStGoal[6]), marker = list(enabled = TRUE, radius=3, symbol = "circle"))%>% hc_add_series(FeedbackDaily, "spline", hcaes(x = datetime_to_timestamp(dateTime), y = StudentGoal07), name=c("Leisure Goal"), showInNavigator = TRUE, visible = as.logical(randStGoal[7]), marker = list(enabled = TRUE, radius=3, symbol = "circle"))%>% hc_add_series(FeedbackDaily, "spline", hcaes(x = datetime_to_timestamp(dateTime), y = StudentGoal08), name=c("Personal Improvement Goal"), showInNavigator = TRUE, visible = as.logical(randStGoal[8]), marker = list(enabled = TRUE, radius=3, symbol = "circle"))%>% hc_add_series(FeedbackDaily, "spline", hcaes(x = datetime_to_timestamp(dateTime), y = StudentGoal09), name=c("Helping Goal"), showInNavigator = TRUE, visible = as.logical(randStGoal[9]), marker = list(enabled = TRUE, radius=3, symbol = "circle"))%>% hc_add_series(FeedbackDaily, "spline", hcaes(x = datetime_to_timestamp(dateTime), y = StudentGoal10), name=c("Spiritual Goal"), showInNavigator = TRUE, visible = as.logical(randStGoal[10]), marker = list(enabled = TRUE, radius=3, symbol = "circle"))%>% hc_colors(brewer.pal(10, "Dark2"))%>% hc_legend(enabled = TRUE)%>% hc_plotOptions( line = list( dataLabels = list(enabled = F), enableMouseTracking = TRUE, showInNavigator = TRUE) )%>% hc_rangeSelector( verticalAlign = "top", buttons = list( list(type = 'all', text = 'All'), list(type = 'day', count = 14, text = '14d'), list(type = 'day', count = 7, text = '7d'), list(type = 'hour', count = 48, text = '48h'), list(type = 'hour', count = 24, text = '24h') )) ``` Note: You can hide or display lines by selecting and de-selecting them in the legend below the graph. You can also hover over the lines to see the exact values. You can focus on a specific time period by using the zoom buttons and the 'From'-'To' fields above the graph, the range selector below the graph or by simply selecting a range within the graph with your mouse or finger (click and drag).

Your Attitudes towards the Dutch

Towards the end of every Recap you reported how you feel towards the Dutch (i.e., the feeling thermometer). Below you can find a graph that illustrates how your feelings towards the Dutch changed over the past `r as.numeric(as.Date(Sys.Date())-as.Date(AOTM_Pre$ended))-1` days. ```{r echo=FALSE, message=FALSE, warning=FALSE} highcharter::highchart(type = "stock") %>% hc_chart(type = "line", zoomType = "x") %>% #hc_title(text = "Your Attitudes towards the Dutch") %>% hc_xAxis(type = "datetime") %>% hc_yAxis(title = list(text = "Feeling Thermometer Dutch"), min = 0, max = 100, showLastLabel = T, showFirstLabel = T, labels = list(format = "{value}°"), plotLines = list( list(label = list(text = "very cold"), color = "#'FF0000", width = 2, value = 0), list(label = list(text = "neutral"), color = "#'FF0000", width = 2, value = 50), list(label = list(text = "very warm"), color = "#'FF0000", width = 2, value = 100))) %>% hc_plotOptions(line = list( dataLabels = list(enabled = F), enableMouseTracking = TRUE) ) %>% hc_add_series(FeedbackDaily, "spline", hcaes(datetime_to_timestamp(dateTime), AttitudesDutch), name="Feeling", color = "darkred", marker = list(enabled = TRUE, radius=3))%>% hc_rangeSelector( verticalAlign = "top", buttons = list( list(type = 'all', text = 'All'), list(type = 'day', count = 14, text = '14d'), list(type = 'day', count = 7, text = '7d'), list(type = 'hour', count = 48, text = '48h'), list(type = 'hour', count = 24, text = '24h') )) ``` Note: You can hover over the line to see the exact values. You can focus on a specific time period by using the zoom buttons and the 'From'-'To' fields above the graph, the range selector below the graph or by simply selecting a range within the graph with your mouse or finger (click and drag).

Your Personality

In the post-questionnaire we asked you a few short questions related to your personality. Below you can see a plot that represents those personality scores. If you are interested in learning more about them, check out: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_Five_personality_traits ```{r echo=FALSE, message=FALSE, warning=FALSE} library(radarchart) extraversion <- mean(c(AOTM_Post$bigFive01*-1+6, AOTM_Post$bigFive06)) agreeableness <- mean(c(AOTM_Post$bigFive07*-1+6, AOTM_Post$bigFive02)) conscientiousness <- mean(c(AOTM_Post$bigFive03*-1+6, AOTM_Post$bigFive08)) neuroticism <- mean(c(AOTM_Post$bigFive04*-1+6, AOTM_Post$bigFive09)) openness <- mean(c(AOTM_Post$bigFive05*-1+6, AOTM_Post$bigFive10)) labs <- c("Openness", "Conscientiousness", "Extraversion", "Agreeableness", "Neuroticism") scores <- list( "You" = c(openness, conscientiousness, extraversion, agreeableness, neuroticism) ) radarchart::chartJSRadar(scores = scores, labs = labs, maxScale = 5) ```

The next Recap will automatically show up in this window, so you can keep this window open or close it until the next invitation e-mail.

units.subject: Evening Recap
units.body:
`r sample(c("Hi","Hey","Good evening","Hello"), 1, replace=TRUE)` `r AOTM_Eligibility$name`, Your afternoon Experience Recap for `r format(Sys.Date(),"%A %B %d")` is ready for you. Follow this link to the short Survey:
Start the Recap now
Please make sure to fill in the survey as soon as possible. It really just takes four minutes. (Keep in mind that this link expires at 01:30 o'clock tonight) `r sample(c("All the best,","Best wishes,","Cheers,","Have a good night,","Have a nice evening,"), 1, replace=TRUE)` The International Experience Study Team

units.subject: 2nd Recontact
units.body:
`r sample(c("Hi","Hey","Hello","Good morning"), 1, replace=TRUE)` `r AOTM_Eligibility$name`, You have reached the end of the daily recaps. There is only the conclusion questionnaire left for which you will earn again 4 Euro (yes, we increased payment by 1 Euro :) ). It is nonetheless also shorter than the first conclusion questionnaire that you filled out 30 days ago. Once you have completed the 2nd Recontact, you will receive your payment for the time period between the first conclusion questionnaire and this second recontact. It may be the case that you have not received the payment for the first period. Please excuse us for the delay. We will ensure that the financial department hurries up.
To the 2nd Recontact
Please make sure to follow the link as soon as possible. Thanks again for all your amazing work, The International Experience Study Team

units.subject: Your Feedback
units.body:
Hi `r AOTM_Eligibility$name`, Thank you again for participating in the International Experience Study! To return to the debriefing and the full feedback click here:
Debriefing and Feedback
All the best, The International Experience Study Team

Thank you for participating!


You earned:
Sections Euro
Entry Questionnaire 2 €
`r length(na.omit(AOTM_Daily$ended))` Experience Recaps   `r length(na.omit(AOTM_Daily$ended))` €
Exit Questionnaire 4 €
Recontact 4 €
Total `r 2+4+4+length(na.omit(AOTM_Daily$ended))` €

Debriefing:
Once again thank you very much for your hard work in the study. Your effort will help us understand the challenges people face when coming to a new country. We also hope to gain a better understanding of how positive and negative interactions with people from different countries influence attitudes and behavior in the long run. The network of interaction partners you built up over the last month will help us understand how interactions with the same or different individuals influence attitudes and behavior towards other individuals. If you have any further questions about the study or your participation, please do not hesitate to contact us at: j.kreienkamp@rug.nl or m.agostini@rug.nl

Your Personal Feedback Dashboard

**Below you can see your responses. Keep in mind that only you have access to this screen and no other person can see what you are seeing. If you decide to continue with the study, we will update your feedback every day. Also, if there are any variables you would be especially interested in feel free to write us an e-mail and we will include them in the daily feedback (j.kreienkap@rug.nl/ m.agostini@rug.nl).**

Your Interactions

Over the past `r as.numeric(as.Date(Sys.Date())-as.Date(AOTM_Pre$ended))-1` days you reported on `r length(na.omit(AOTM_Daily$ended))` Interactions. The following graph shows you what types of interactions you entered: ```{r echo=FALSE, message=FALSE, warning=FALSE} #install.packages("htmlwidgets") library(htmlwidgets) library(highcharter) library(RColorBrewer) library(readr) library(dplyr) Interaction <- as.data.frame(table(AOTM_Daily %>% filter(!is.na(ended)) %>% select(Interaction))) names(Interaction) <- c("Type", "Frequency") highcharter::highchart() %>% hc_chart(type = "column") %>% hc_xAxis(categories = names(Interaction)) %>% hc_add_series(name = "Dutch", data = Interaction %>% filter(Type=="Dutch") %>% select(Frequency) %>% as.numeric()) %>% hc_add_series(name = "Non-Dutch", data = Interaction %>% filter(Type=="Non-Dutch") %>% select(Frequency) %>% as.numeric()) %>% hc_add_series(name = "No Interaction", data = Interaction %>% filter(Type=="no interaction") %>% select(Frequency) %>% as.numeric()) %>% #hc_title(text = "Your Interactions")%>% hc_colors(brewer.pal(3, "Set2")) ```

Your Well-Being

At every Recap you reported your general well-being (from very negative to very positve; the slider with the sad to happy smiley). Below you can find a graph that illustrates how your well-being changed over the course of the past `r as.numeric(as.Date(Sys.Date())-as.Date(AOTM_Pre$ended))-1` days. ```{r echo=FALSE, message=FALSE, warning=FALSE} FeedbackDaily <- AOTM_Daily %>% filter(!is.na(ended)) %>% select(ended, exWB, energy, afraid, angry, Autonomy, Competence, RelatednessOther, RelatednessSelf, RelatednessNoInteraction, AttitudesDutch, Interaction, StudentGoal01, StudentGoal02, StudentGoal03, StudentGoal04, StudentGoal05, StudentGoal06, StudentGoal07, StudentGoal08, StudentGoal09, StudentGoal10) FeedbackDaily$dateTime <- as.POSIXct(FeedbackDaily$ended) FeedbackDaily$RelatednessNoInteractionRev <- FeedbackDaily$RelatednessNoInteraction*-1+100 FeedbackDaily$Relatedness <- rowMeans(FeedbackDaily %>% select(RelatednessOther, RelatednessSelf, RelatednessNoInteractionRev), na.rm = T) highcharter::highchart(type = "stock") %>% hc_chart(type = "line", zoomType = "x") %>% #hc_title(text = "Your Well-Being") %>% hc_xAxis(type = "datetime") %>% hc_yAxis(title = list(text = "Well-Being"), min = -100, max = 100, showLastLabel = T, showFirstLabel = T, plotLines = list( list(label = list(text = "Neutral"), color = "#'FF0000", width = 2, value = 0), list(label = list(text = "Negative"), color = "#'FF0000", width = 2, value = -100), list(label = list(text = "Positive"), color = "#'FF0000", width = 2, value = 100))) %>% hc_plotOptions(line = list( dataLabels = list(enabled = F), enableMouseTracking = TRUE) ) %>% hc_add_series(FeedbackDaily, "spline", hcaes(datetime_to_timestamp(dateTime), exWB), name="Well-Being", marker = list(enabled = TRUE, radius=3))%>% hc_rangeSelector( verticalAlign = "top", buttons = list( list(type = 'all', text = 'All'), list(type = 'day', count = 14, text = '14d'), list(type = 'day', count = 7, text = '7d'), list(type = 'hour', count = 48, text = '48h'), list(type = 'hour', count = 24, text = '24h') )) ``` Note: You can hover over the line to see the exact values. You can focus on a specific time period by using the zoom buttons and the 'From'-'To' fields above the graph, the range selector below the graph or by simply selecting a range within the graph with your mouse or finger (click and drag).

Your Mood

At every Recap you also reported your emotional state of worry, anger and your enery levels. Below you can find a graph that illustrates how your states changed over the course of the past `r as.numeric(as.Date(Sys.Date())-as.Date(AOTM_Pre$ended))-1` days. ```{r echo=FALSE, message=FALSE, warning=FALSE} highcharter::highchart(type = "stock") %>% hc_chart(type = "line", zoomType = "x") %>% #hc_title(text = "Your Mood") %>% hc_xAxis(type = "datetime") %>% hc_yAxis(title = list(text = "Mood"), min = 0, max = 100, showLastLabel = T, showFirstLabel = T, opposite = TRUE, plotLines = list( list(label = list(text = "not at all"), color = "#'FF0000", width = 2, value = 0), list(label = list(text = "A great deal"), color = "#'FF0000", width = 2, value = 100))) %>% hc_add_series(FeedbackDaily, "spline", hcaes(datetime_to_timestamp(dateTime), energy), name="Energy", showInNavigator = TRUE, marker = list(enabled = TRUE, radius=3, symbol = "circle"))%>% hc_add_series(FeedbackDaily, "spline", hcaes(datetime_to_timestamp(dateTime), afraid), name="Worry", showInNavigator = TRUE, marker = list(enabled = TRUE, radius=3, symbol = "circle"))%>% hc_add_series(FeedbackDaily, "spline", hcaes(datetime_to_timestamp(dateTime), angry), name="Anger", showInNavigator = TRUE, marker = list(enabled = TRUE, radius=3, symbol = "circle"))%>% hc_colors(brewer.pal(3, "Set1"))%>% hc_legend(enabled = TRUE)%>% hc_plotOptions( line = list( dataLabels = list(enabled = F), enableMouseTracking = TRUE, showInNavigator = TRUE) )%>% hc_rangeSelector( verticalAlign = "top", buttons = list( list(type = 'all', text = 'All'), list(type = 'day', count = 14, text = '14d'), list(type = 'day', count = 7, text = '7d'), list(type = 'hour', count = 48, text = '48h'), list(type = 'hour', count = 24, text = '24h') )) ``` Note: You can hide or display lines by selecting and de-selecting them in the legend below the graph. You can also hover over the lines to see the exact values. You can focus on a specific time period by using the zoom buttons and the 'From'-'To' fields above the graph, the range selector below the graph or by simply selecting a range within the graph with your mouse or finger (click and drag).

Your Psychological Needs

There is a growing body of literature assuming that humans have three basic psychological needs (e.g., Deci and Ryan, 2008). (1) The need to have an impact on the self or one's environment (need for competence), (2) the need to experience a sense of choice and psychological freedom in everyday life (need for autonomy), and (3) the need to care about and be cared about by others (need to belong). Over the past `r as.numeric(as.Date(Sys.Date())-as.Date(AOTM_Pre$ended))-1` days we asked you to report how much these three needs were fulfilled during your interactions or your everyday life. Below you can see how your three needs (co-)developed over time. Please keep in mind that the need to belong can vary quite strongly depending on whether you had an interaction or not. ```{r echo=FALSE, message=FALSE, warning=FALSE} highcharter::highchart(type = "stock") %>% hc_chart(type = "line", zoomType = "x") %>% #hc_title(text = "Your Mood") %>% hc_xAxis(type = "datetime") %>% hc_yAxis(title = list(text = "Mood"), min = 0, max = 100, showLastLabel = T, showFirstLabel = T, opposite = TRUE, plotLines = list( list(label = list(text = "not at all"), color = "#'FF0000", width = 2, value = 0), list(label = list(text = "A great deal"), color = "#'FF0000", width = 2, value = 100))) %>% hc_add_series(FeedbackDaily, "spline", hcaes(x = datetime_to_timestamp(dateTime), y = Autonomy), name="Autonomy", showInNavigator = TRUE, marker = list(enabled = TRUE, radius=3, symbol = "circle"))%>% hc_add_series(FeedbackDaily, "spline", hcaes(datetime_to_timestamp(dateTime), Competence), name="Competence", showInNavigator = TRUE, marker = list(enabled = TRUE, radius=3, symbol = "circle"))%>% hc_add_series(FeedbackDaily, "spline", showInNavigator = TRUE, hcaes(datetime_to_timestamp(dateTime), Relatedness), name="Relatedness", marker = list(enabled = TRUE, radius=3, symbol = "circle"))%>% hc_colors(brewer.pal(3, "Dark2"))%>% hc_legend(enabled = TRUE)%>% hc_plotOptions( line = list( dataLabels = list(enabled = F), enableMouseTracking = TRUE, showInNavigator = TRUE) )%>% hc_rangeSelector( verticalAlign = "top", buttons = list( list(type = 'all', text = 'All'), list(type = 'day', count = 14, text = '14d'), list(type = 'day', count = 7, text = '7d'), list(type = 'hour', count = 48, text = '48h'), list(type = 'hour', count = 24, text = '24h') )) ``` Note: You can hide or display lines by selecting and de-selecting them in the legend below the graph. You can also hover over the lines to see the exact values. You can focus on a specific time period by using the zoom buttons and the 'From'-'To' fields above the graph, the range selector below the graph or by simply selecting a range within the graph with your mouse or finger (click and drag).

Your Daily Goals

Every day we asked you how important different goals were to you. The following graph illustrated how your daily goals changed over the course of this study. To not overwhelm you only one is active but you can click on the legend to see your other goals. ```{r echo=FALSE, message=FALSE, warning=FALSE} randStGoal <- sample(c("TRUE", "FALSE", "FALSE", "FALSE", "FALSE", "FALSE", "FALSE", "FALSE", "FALSE", "FALSE")) highcharter::highchart(type = "stock") %>% hc_chart(type = "line", zoomType = "x") %>% #hc_title(text = "Your Mood") %>% hc_xAxis(type = "#'FF0000", width = 2, value = 0), list(label = list(text = "Very important"), color = "#'FF0000", width = 2, value = 100))) %>% hc_add_series(FeedbackDaily, "spline", hcaes(x = datetime_to_timestamp(dateTime), y = StudentGoal01), name=c("Social Support Goal"), showInNavigator = TRUE, visible = as.logical(randStGoal[1]), marker = list(enabled = TRUE, radius=3, symbol = "circle"))%>% hc_add_series(FeedbackDaily, "spline", hcaes(x = datetime_to_timestamp(dateTime), y = StudentGoal02), name=c("Romantic Goal"), showInNavigator = TRUE, visible = as.logical(randStGoal[2]), marker = list(enabled = TRUE, radius=3, symbol = "circle"))%>% hc_add_series(FeedbackDaily, "spline", hcaes(x = datetime_to_timestamp(dateTime), y = StudentGoal03), name=c("Academic Goal"), showInNavigator = TRUE, visible = as.logical(randStGoal[3]), marker = list(enabled = TRUE, radius=3, symbol = "circle"))%>% hc_add_series(FeedbackDaily, "spline", hcaes(x = hc_add_series(FeedbackDaily, "spline", hcaes(x = datetime_to_timestamp(dateTime), y = StudentGoal05), name=c("Financial Goal"), showInNavigator = TRUE, visible = as.logical(randStGoal[5]), marker = list(enabled = TRUE, radius=3, symbol = "circle"))%>% hc_add_series(FeedbackDaily, "spline", hcaes(x = datetime_to_timestamp(dateTime), y = StudentGoal06), name=c("Health Goal"), showInNavigator = TRUE, visible = as.logical(randStGoal[6]), marker = list(enabled = TRUE, radius=3, symbol = "circle"))%>% hc_add_series(FeedbackDaily, "spline", hcaes(x = datetime_to_timestamp(dateTime), y = "spline", hcaes(x = datetime_to_timestamp(dateTime), y = StudentGoal08), name=c("Personal Improvement Goal"), showInNavigator = TRUE, visible = as.logical(randStGoal[8]), marker = list(enabled = TRUE, radius=3, symbol = "circle"))%>% hc_add_series(FeedbackDaily, "spline", hcaes(x = datetime_to_timestamp(dateTime), y = StudentGoal09), name=c("Helping Goal"), showInNavigator = TRUE, visible = as.logical(randStGoal[9]), marker = list(enabled = TRUE, radius=3, symbol = "circle"))%>% hc_add_series(FeedbackDaily, "spline", hcaes(x = datetime_to_timestamp(dateTime), y = StudentGoal10),
